Patch Set 1:

Hi Jon,

i think that post https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/32403 all ipv6 enabled interfaces should have an LL addr. What interface type did you see this with?

neale

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> Hi Jon,
> 
> i think that post https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/32403 all ipv6 enabled interfaces should have an LL addr. What interface type did you see this with?
> 
> neale

Hi Neale,

We saw this on various intel ethernet interfaces when using linux-cp/linux-nl. We would configure a global unicast address and an IPv6 VRRP VR. Then if we took the interface down and brought it back up, VPP would crash while the interface was being brought up.

The linux kernel automatically adds a link local address when an interface is brought up and deletes it when the interface is brought down (with default settings for addr_gen_mode which automatically generate a v6 link local address using EUI). This sequence of events would occur:

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> > Patch Set 1:
> > 
> > Hi Jon,
> > 
> > i think that post https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/32403 all ipv6 enabled interfaces should have an LL addr. What interface type did you see this with?
> > 
> > neale
> 
> Hi Neale,
> 
> We saw this on various intel ethernet interfaces when using linux-cp/linux-nl. We would configure a global unicast address and an IPv6 VRRP VR. Then if we took the interface down and brought it back up, VPP would crash while the interface was being brought up.
> 
> The linux kernel automatically adds a link local address when an interface is brought up and deletes it when the interface is brought down (with default settings for addr_gen_mode which automatically generate a v6 link local address using EUI). This sequence of events would occur:

Oops, last reply truncated:

1. bring interface down
2. kernel sends RTM_DELADDR for link local address. 
3. kernel sends RTM_NEWLINK for admin state change.
4. linux-nl processes RTM_DELADDR, disables IPv6 on interface.
5. linux-nl processes RTM_NEWLINK, takes interface down.
6. bring interface up
7. kernel sends RTM_NEWLINK for admin state change
8. kernel sends RTM_NEWADDR for link local address
9. linux-nl processes RTM_NEWLINK, brings up interface.
10. VRRP tries to send multicast messages to join all vrrp routers group. Since interface was disabled for IPv6, no link local address is found and VPP crashes.

The root cause was that linux-nl was always calling ip6_link_disable() when the link local address was deleted. But when it was added, ip6_link_enable() only got called if the interface was not already enabled. It was enabled implicitly by adding a global unicast address, so it would not be enabled again and the lock count would stay at 1. Then when its disabled later, the count goes to 0 so the interface is disabled. Patch set 9 of gerrit change 31122 (https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/31122/9) changes this behavior to fix the issue.

I asked Jon to also submit this VRRP patch. My logic was: if we have seen the code crash someplace, it is good to add an extra check which would prevent it from happening again if some other unexpected condition causes the link local address not to be found.

-Matt

> > > Put back original commentsry this one is not correct
> > 
> > So I added commit message here, describing why I think the original documentation is not correct enough.
> 
> Commit message is irrelevant to the code functionality.

True. But it is relevant for people investigating code changes (including this review process).

> It is desinged to describe telemetry with relation to traffic trial.

The the documentation describes the correct relation, but not clearly enough.
My edits are improving clarity, commit message explains why the edited description is better.

> -2 remains until you will study more why it is like this

Do you mean action/traffic ordering (I think we agree on that) or the specific documentation (we disagree)?
I do know why the ordering is like this.
I do not know why the documentation is exactly like this.

I was thinking about refactoring TrafficGenerator into three layers:
1. Traffic layer: TG initialization, start/stop traffic, return raw text output.
2. Parsing layer: Select STL/ASTF, parse/remember TG counters, track time since previous start/stop.
3. Measurement layer: Insert ramp-ups, compute loss according to transaction type, AbstractMeasurer compatibility.

Maybe more layers, maybe less, depending on code complexity. My point is, I may invent some more words while doing that, so maybe this can wait for that.

Patch Set 8:

> But we cannot have it in upper logic.

Why not?

> As we want upper logic to be independent of what "module is doing".

The upper logic (RxQueue class) offers functionality that modules (traffic scripts) find useful, for example the "ignore" argument to skip over known packets once.
When we find there is another useful functionality (skipping over the IPv6 stuff) used by most (after 32748 all) callers, it makes sense to move the functionality into the upper logic to simplify call sites.

> What if I want to have test for NS_RA?

You introduce another optional argument to control the behavior, see "skip_ip6" added in patch set #8. If you worry about callers in downstream projects, I can make the default False.

Patch Set 10:

Replies with some recap, new info at the end.

>>> This commit makes no sense.

Not much information here.
I guessed you are asking for motivation (so I mentioned lines of code), but it seems I guessed wrong.

>>> It is better to just create function like valid_ip() and leave it in while True: loop while filter will have its name and anybody can override per profile.

I imagined the while loop at call sites, that is why I replied with:

>> Sounds more complicated to me and saves less lines.

But see below.

> If the only criteria for you is GLOC instead of architecture design.

That is some more info (still not much, but better than "no sense").

New guess: When saying "This commit makes no sense.", you were complaining about .recv already doing too much (using select in a loop while ignoring benign signals, and filtering on packets_sent), so adding even more work to the same place is not a good design.
Maybe the "create function like valid_ip() and leave it in while True: loop" part can be applied to the while 1: loop in recv() instead, in which case having a pluggable filter there makes sense _if_ we have additional wrapper that plugs in a default filter to handle packets sent _and_ IPv6.
Traffic scripts with different needs may simply not use that wrapper.

So in patch set #10 I added that wrapper layer as a subclass, and two more wrapper functions to hide more details related to tracking sent packets and getting interface names from TrafficScriptArg.
This makes PacketVerifier significantly longer (+232 -41), but the design should be more readable now (more docstrings, less code per method/function), and savings at call sites still make this a good change from lines point of view overall (+303 -471).

Not sure what do you mean. Maybe this?
